    "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
    "body": "Even bounded requirements have been a big headache. Upstream deps have been rather bad about sticking to proper semver. Even the semver package had a breaking patch version.\r\n\r\nGiven that brownie is primarily a command line tool, I think we need to keep hard pins as the default. However, I definitely see the argument when using brownie as a library. This is more python's fault for not handling packages that can be a library and a package well.\r\n\r\nI think #993 might keep everyone happy:\r\n\r\n1. Normal users doing `pip install eth-brownie` will get hard pins from .txt that won't surprise anyone.\r\n2. People using brownie as a library do `export BROWNIE_LIB=1` and then they can have soft pins.\r\n3. When brownie is going to release, the dev does `pip-compile --upgrade` and tests things. if something is broken, they can tweak the soft pins and re-run pip-compile.",
